Pseudogonatodes quihuai
is an Andean species and its geographic distribution appears to be restricted to midelevations on the eastern slope of the Cordillera de MÃ©rida . Although the ongoing loss of premontane and montane forest coverage in this region (
;
) may pose a major threat to this silvicolous species, it seems to thrive in shaded coffee plantations and partially modified forests, and its range likely extends within the Ramal de Calderas National Park. However, taking into account that this lizard species is only known from a few specimens and from only two nearby localities, and that its ecology, population status, and other potential threats are virtually unknown, we suggest categorizing
P. quihuai
as âData Deficientâ (DD) according to the IUCN Red List (2022). We stress the need to increase our knowledge on the distribution and natural history of this species in order to properly assess its conservation status.
